TY  - JOUR
T1  - Antecedents of Organizational Slack
AU  - Sharfman, Mark P.
AU  - Wolf, Gerrit
AU  - Chase, Richard B.
AU  - Tansik, David A.
Y1  - 1988/10/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1988.4307484
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1988.4307484
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 601
EP  - 614
VL  - 13
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Organizational slack has been widely discussed, but only in its role as an antecedent of performance, political behavior, bankruptcy, and other phenomena. A model that describes the antecedents of organizational slack is presented here. It contains three sets of predictors: environmental contingencies, organizational characteristics, and the values and beliefs of dominant coalition. Hypotheses detailing how each set of predictors leads to the development of different levels and types of slack resources are presented.
AB  - Organizational slack has been widely discussed, but only in its role as an antecedent of performance, political behavior, bankruptcy, and other phenomena. A model that describes the antecedents of organizational slack is presented here. It contains three sets of predictors: environmental contingencies, organizational characteristics, and the values and beliefs of dominant coalition. Hypotheses detailing how each set of predictors leads to the development of different levels and types of slack resources are presented.
