TY  - JOUR
T1  - American Manufacturing Unions' Stasis: A Paradigmatic Perspective
AU  - Murray, Alan I.
AU  - Reshef, Yonatan
Y1  - 1988/10/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1988.4307505
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1988.4307505
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 615
EP  - 626
VL  - 13
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This paper argues that American manufacturing unions, if they are to revitalize themselves numerically and politically, must develop new strategies in order to cope with rapidly changing environments. After reviewing two action paradigms that are available for unions, we show why manufacturing unions have adopted the economic rather than political paradigm. We argue that the economic paradigm is viable only under a specific set of conditions that no longer apply. Finally, long-term adherence to the economic paradigm produces resistance to paradigmatic change in response to external changes in many unions. As an illustration, we use the American auto industry.
AB  - This paper argues that American manufacturing unions, if they are to revitalize themselves numerically and politically, must develop new strategies in order to cope with rapidly changing environments. After reviewing two action paradigms that are available for unions, we show why manufacturing unions have adopted the economic rather than political paradigm. We argue that the economic paradigm is viable only under a specific set of conditions that no longer apply. Finally, long-term adherence to the economic paradigm produces resistance to paradigmatic change in response to external changes in many unions. As an illustration, we use the American auto industry.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1988.4307505
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1988.4307505
Y2  - 2026/04/24
